CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; SACRAMENTO; PANEL URGES LAWMAKER VOTE ON INITIATIVES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A prestigious commission called for significant changes in the initiative 
process, recommending that the Legislature vote on proposed ballot measures 
before they are placed on the ballot.If lawmakers approve them, such measures 
would become law without being on the ballot. Those measures rejected by the 
Legislature would go on the statewide ballot. The commission, headed by former 
Legislative Analyst A. Alan Post, also recommended that lawmakers be free to 
make changes to the proposed initiatives, as long as the proponents agree. 
Initiatives would still have to qualify by signature petitions as they do now. 
Assemblyman Jim Costa (D-Fresno) said he intends to put the recommendations 
into the form of bills to be considered by the Legislature this year. 
</P>
