<HEADLINE>
<P>
EXECUTIVE SUITE: MCA TO INCREASE RESPONSIBILITIES OF AL TELLER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 MCA Music Entertainment Group Chairman Al Teller will get additional 
responsibilities with corporate parent MCA Inc., sources close to the company 
say. 
</P>
<P>
 The move is viewed partly as a reward for what is expected to be a record year 
for the music company in 1993, as well as a reflection of Teller's increasing 
role at MCA in areas such as technology. 
</P>
<P>
 Sources speculated that there will be an additional title for for Teller -- 
who will continue to oversee music -- probably as an MCA executive vice 
president. Teller is credited with a successful gamble on the surprise career 
revival of singer Meat Loaf, whose "Bat Out of Hell II" album turned out to be 
MCA's biggest seller last year. 
</P>
<P>
 * Richard Cohen is leaving Walt Disney's Buena Vista Home Video Worldwide, 
where he was executive vice president, to head MGM/UA Home Entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
 * Sony Corp. of America named James N. Fiedler to oversee its U.S. 
intellectual property unit. 
</P>
<P>
 * USA Networks named Cynthia Wurtz vice president of affiliate relations for 
its western region. 
</P>
<P>
 * Robert Messa is Live Home Video's new East Coast regional sales 
representative. 
</P>
<P>
 * James F. Griffiths has rejoined Fox Inc. as a senior vice president. 
</P>
<P>
 * Paramount Home Video named Jeff Radoycis executive director of sales and 
marketing for multimedia products. 
</P>
<P>
 * Paramount Licensing Group named Debbi Petrasek vice president of domestic 
licensing. 
</P>
<P>
 * Sharon Sheer was named senior director of compensation and benefits at EMI 
Records Group. 
</P>
</TEXT>
