<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: RESEDA; $25,000 OFFERED FOR LEADS IN SLAYING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TERESA ANN WILLIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles City Council this week authorized a $25,000 reward for 
information leading to the identification and apprehension of the suspects 
responsible for killing Lea Graf, co-owner of a Army-Navy surplus store in 
Reseda, last November. 
</P>
<P>
 Graf, 61, was killed when she and her husband were overtaken by two gunmen as 
they were closing their Reseda Boulevard store for the night. 
</P>
<P>
 Police have made no arrests and still have no suspects. They asked 
Councilwoman Laura Chick to petition the council for reward money last month. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're hoping that the reward announcement will generate some leads," said Los 
Angeles Police Lt. George Rock. 
</P>
<P>
 The couple, married 34 years, moved to Los Angeles from Israel in 1960. After 
dabbling in other business ventures, they set up the surplus store that became 
an institution. 
</P>
<P>
 Bernard Graf, Lea's husband, was injured in the attack, but managed to shoot 
back at the gunmen seven times before they fled. 
</P>
<P>
 "I don't know how effective it (a reward) has been in the past, but I hope 
we'll have some response from somebody," Graf said. "We're hoping maybe this 
time something will come up." TERESA ANN WILLIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
