<HEADLINE>
<P>
SANTA CLARITA / ANTELOPE VALLEY; NASA FACILITY WILL GAIN ITS INDEPENDENCE; 
NASA: DRYDEN FLIGHT RESEARCH FACILITY HAD BEEN ON ITS OWN, BUT HAS BEEN A PART 
OF THE AMES RESEARCH CENTER SINCE 1981. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SHARON MOESER, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 NASA's Dryden Flight Research Facility on Thursday finally received what it's 
been seeking for years -- independence. 
</P>
<P>
 In an address that detailed changes within the space agency, Daniel S. Goldin, 
National Aeronautics and Space Administration administrator, said Dryden would 
become a separate entity.Dryden now operates as a facility of NASA's Ames 
Research Center in Mountain View. 
</P>
<P>
 Dryden will formally gain its independence March 1, according to Goldin. 
Dryden chief Kenneth Szalai was named director of the facility. 
</P>
<P>
 Goldin addressed NASA employees across the country via the agency's satellite 
television network and also made a public speech in Washington. He said the 
changes and appointments outlined Thursday "will enhance and strengthen the 
agency's programs and institutions." 
</P>
<P>
 He said the changes follow President Clinton's "goal to make government less 
expensive and more efficient, and to reinvigorate NASA." 
</P>
<P>
 Goldin also announced appointments to several posts at NASA headquarters and 
named new directors for several centers, including Johnson Space Center, where 
Carolyn Huntoon will take the reins. 
</P>
<P>
 Goldin said giving Dryden its independence "reflects the commitment on the 
part of NASA to reduce layers of management and empower operating organizations 
to carry out their mission with maximum benefit to the country." 
</P>
<P>
 Dryden, where NASA flight tests its research aircraft, had previously been on 
its own, but in 1981 was made a component of Ames. 
</P>
</TEXT>
